The comet which astronomers had been watching with great interest because it was passing so close to the sun on Thursday appears to have been destroyed.

Comet ISON, which had been branded the 'comet of the century,' was making its closest approach to the sun, skimming about 730,000 miles above its surface, when it disappeared from the view of space telescopes.

'Comet ISON probably has not survived this journey,' Karl Battams with the U.S. Naval Research Laboratory and the NASA Comet ISON Observing Campaign told a NASA Google Hangout on Thursday.

