Experts said it appears ISON broke up into chunks and the sun evaporated it.

Observers had been hoping that ISON would survive its Thanksgiving Day close encounter with the sun and emerge to put on a big sky show in December.

'We have never seen a comet like this,' Naval Research Laboratory astrophysicist Karl Battams had said during a NASA news conference on Tuesday. 'It has been behaving strangely.'

According to Johns Hopkins University scientist Carey Lisse, even if the comet has died there is a good chance that people on Earth will get an interesting cosmic show. The comet's remnants could paint the sky with a wide swath of green in the Northern Hemisphere.

